  "chunk_index": 10,
  "summary": "Hercule Poirot questions a waitress named Lucie regarding guests who made phone calls. Lucie reveals that a young lady in a white dress called upon entering the venue, and another lady made a call from a booth after exiting the cloakroom. Suspecting that something is about to happen, Poirot observes the guests during dinner.\n\nBarton Russell proposes a toast to his late wife, Eileen, whose death occurred four years ago today. He explains that the dinner is a commemoration of her passing, which took place during a dinner in New York attended by himself, Stephen Carter, Tony Chappel, Lola Valdes, and a sixteen-year-old Polly Weatherby. Although the official verdict for Eileen's death was suicide via cyanide, Russell claims he believes she was murdered by someone present at that New York dinner who planted cyanide in her handbag. He expresses his intention to uncover the truth.\n\nAs the lights dim for a cabaret performance, a Black singer performs a mournful song, creating an atmosphere that the guests note is strikingly similar to the night of the New York tragedy. When the lights return after the performance, the guests discover that Polly Weatherby has slumped over the table, dead. Lola compares the death to that of \"Alice\" in New York. Poirot examines Polly and confirms her death, noting the scent of cyanide, similar to bitter almonds, in her cup. A distressed Barton Russell suggests that Polly may have seen something suspicious during the original incident in New York.",
